8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1029, L.D. 1571, “An Act to Modify
10 Certification Standards for Full-time Teachers in Public Charter Schools and for
11 Educational Technicians”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'An Act to Modify Certification Standards for Full-time Teachers in Public Charter
14 Schools and Standards for Reissuance of Educational Technician Certificates'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
16 following:
17 'Sec. 1. 20-A MRSA §2412, sub-§6, ¶B, as enacted by PL 2011, c. 414, §5, is
18 amended to read:
19 B. All full-time teachers in a public charter school must either hold an appropriate
20 teaching certificate or become certified within 3 years of the date they are hired, except
21 for those with an advanced degree, professional certification or unique expertise or
22 experience in the curricular area in which they teach.
23 This paragraph is repealed August 1, 2026.
24 Sec. 2. 20-A MRSA §2412, sub-§6, ¶B-1 is enacted to read:
25 B-1. Beginning August 1, 2026, all full-time teachers in a public charter school must
26 hold an appropriate teaching certificate.
27 Sec. 3. 20-A MRSA §13019-H, sub-§6, as enacted by PL 2023, c. 442, §2 and
28 reallocated by RR 2023, c. 1, Pt. A, §7, is amended to read:
29 6. Reissuance; retired educational technician. The commissioner may issue an
30 educational technician certificate to a person who has been receiving a retirement benefit
31 from the State Employee and Teacher Retirement Program established under Title 5,
32 section 17602 for no more than 5 years until July 31, 2026 and for no more than 3 years
33 beginning August 1, 2026 and who, immediately prior to receiving that benefit, possessed
34 an active educational technician certificate in good standing that has subsequently lapsed.
